Common Types of HTTP Requests
1. GET

Meaning: Retrieve data from the server.

Use case: When you want to fetch or read data (like getting a webpage or fetching user info).

Example: Loading a webpage, fetching a list of products.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. POST

Meaning: Send data to the server to create something new.

Use case: When submitting a form, creating a new user, or uploading a file.

Example: Registering on a website, posting a comment.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


3. PUT

Meaning: Update or replace existing data on the server.

Use case: When you want to update an entire resource (like updating all user info).

Example: Updating a user profile completely.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


4. PATCH

Meaning: Partially update existing data on the server.

Use case: When you want to update only certain fields of a resource.

Example: Changing just the email or password of a user.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


5. DELETE

Meaning: Remove data from the server.

Use case: When you want to delete a resource.

Example: Deleting a user account or a post.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


6. HEAD

Meaning: Same as GET but only fetches headers, no body.

Use case: To check if a resource exists or to get metadata without downloading the whole content.

Example: Checking if a file is available before downloading.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


7. OPTIONS

Meaning: Ask the server which HTTP methods it supports for a resource.

Use case: To know what actions are allowed on a URL.

Example: Preflight request in CORS to check permissions.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
